ethtool --phy-statistics eth0
ethtool eth0
ethtool -S eth0
From ethtool -S counters, the best early indicators are:
	in_fcs_error (CRC/FCS)
	in_rx_error
	in_fragments, in_jabber, in_oversize (usually zero; nonzero is suspicious)
	in_discards (can be congestion too, but watch trends)

1️ Cable / PHY Features

These reflect electrical margin, noise, connector degradation.
Retrieve from:
ethtool --phy-statistics XP1
(and link state from XP1)
Features
Primary early-warning signals
	- phy_receive_errors_rate Δphy_receive_errors_copper / 60 Source: ethtool --phy-statistics XP1
	- phy_idle_errors_rate Δphy_idle_errors / 60 Source: same
These are closest to real physical degradation.
Link stability
	- link_flap (1 if link changed since last minute)
	- Source: ethtool XP1 or /sys/class/net/XP1/operstate
	- flaps_1h (rolling count)
	- time_since_last_link_down
Connector problems show up here before permanent failure.

Temperature context
temp_c
temp_delta_10m
Source: /sys/class/hwmon/...

2 Port MAC / Switch (Physical Port Symptoms)
These show corrupted frames arriving from that specific cable.
Retrieve from:
ethtool -S XP1
(not masterif — use the actual DSA port netdev)

Features
Integrity (most important)
	- fcs_rate Δin_fcs_error / 60 fcs_per_million_pkts
	- 1e6 * Δin_fcs_error / max(Δrx_packets,1)
	- rx_error_rate Δin_rx_error / 60
	- bad_octets_rate Δin_bad_octets / 60

Malformed frames
- fragment_rate = Δin_fragments / 60
- jabber_rate = Δin_jabber / 60
- oversize_rate = Δin_oversize / 60
- undersize_rate = Δin_undersize / 60
These are rare. If they rise → something is electrically wrong.

Drops at ingress
- port_discards_rate Δin_discards / 60

3️ CPU / Master MAC (Host-Side Context)

These tell you if the system is overloaded — not the cable.
Retrieve from:
ethtool -S masterif

Features

Host congestion
- host_rx_drop_rate ΔIEEE_rx_drop / 60
- host_tx_drop_rate ΔIEEE_tx_drop / 60
- tx_dropped_rate Δtx_dropped / 60

If these rise but XP1 integrity is clean → not cable.

Host CRC (secondary check)
- host_rx_crc_rate Δrx_crc_errors / 60
Less specific than per-port in_fcs_error.

4 Traffic Context (prevents false positives)
Retrieve from:
Preferably XP1 for port-specific load
(or masterif if easier)

Load
- rx_bps = Δrx_bytes * 8 / 60
- tx_bps = Δtx_bytes * 8 / 60
- pps = (Δrx_packets + Δtx_packets) / 60
- utilization = (rx_bps + tx_bps) / link_speed_bps
Errors under heavy utilization are more meaningful than errors at idle.


Minimal Clean Feature Set (if you want it tight)
Cable/PHY (XP1)
- phy_receive_errors_rate
- phy_idle_errors_rate
- link_flap
- temp_c

Port Integrity (XP1)
- fcs_per_million_pkts
- rx_error_rate
- port_discards_rate

Host Context (masterif)
- host_rx_drop_rate
- utilization


These are your “instantaneous” signals.
That’s 9 features. That’s already strong.

========================================
Level 1 — Raw (per minute)
From XP1 / masterif:
	fcs_per_million_pkts
	phy_receive_errors_rate
	port_discards_rate
	link_flap
	utilization
	temp_c

These are your “instantaneous” signals.

Level 2 — Windowed (over last 10 minutes)
These are computed from the raw ones:
	mean_fcs_per_million
	max_fcs_per_million
	mean_phy_rxerr
	max_phy_rxerr
	mean_discards
	max_discards
	flaps_10m (sum of link_flap)
	mean_utilization
	mean_temp
	temp_slope_10m = temp_now − temp_10_minutes_ago
========================================


TESTING:

Mild bending usually won’t cause measurable errors on a good short cable.
Most links only show errors under load, because idle traffic doesn’t stress signal integrity.
Unplug/replug mainly gives carrier drops and link_flap, not subtle degradation.

Heavy traffic generate with:
iperf3 -s            # on peer
iperf3 -c <peer_ip> -t 300 -P 4

For reproducible non-disconnect faults, use stronger conditions:

Long/poor cable (old Cat5, damaged patch lead).
- Extra connectors/couplers in series.
- Strong bend right at RJ45 strain relief while iperf3 is running.
- EMI exposure (near power brick/motor cable).
- Force speed higher (e.g., 1G) and run heavy traffic.

Idea is to make error counters move (traffic + physical disturbance).